</li>
<li id="cite_note-toomer1964Review-113"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-toomer1964Review_113-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/G._J._Toomer" class="mw-redirect" title="G. J. Toomer">G. J. Toomer</a>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/228328?pg=464">Review on JSTOR, Toomer's 1964 review of Matthias Schramm (1963) <i>Ibn Al-Haythams Weg Zur Physik</i></a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170326070235/http://www.jstor.org/stable/228328?pg=464">Archived</a> 26 March 2017 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a> Toomer p. 464: "Schramm sums up [Ibn Al-Haytham's] achievement in the development of scientific method.", p. 465: "Schramm has demonstrated .. beyond any dispute that Ibn al-Haytham is a major figure in the Islamic scientific tradition, particularly in the creation of experimental techniques." p. 465: "Only when the influence of ibn al-Haytam and others on the mainstream of later medieval physical writings has been seriously investigated can Schramm's claim that ibn al-Haytam was the true founder of modern physics be evaluated."</span>
